> - **Course:** PEMRT415 - OBJECT ORIENTED PROGRAMMING
> - **Module:** Module 2
> - **Topic:** Object Oriented Programming in Java - Class Fundamentals

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Class (Java, KTU Definition):** A class in Java is a **user-defined blueprint / template** from which objects are created. It encapsulates **data (attributes/fields)** and **behaviour (methods)** into a single logical unit. A class is a **reference type** in Java and acts as the fundamental building block of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP).

In the KTU 2024 Scheme syllabus, Class Fundamentals is listed under **Module 2 – Introduction to Object Oriented Programming & Java**. The expected learning outcomes demand that the student must be able to:

- **CO2:** *Illustrate the concept of classes, objects, encapsulation and abstraction using Java.*
- **CO3:** *Apply object-oriented principles to design simple Java programs.*

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy – The Blueprint of a House

Imagine an **architect's blueprint** of a house.

- The **blueprint itself is NOT a house** — you cannot live inside it. (This is the *Class*.)
- From that one blueprint, you can build **many independent houses** — each with its own colour, owner, and furniture. (These are *Objects* / *Instances*.)
- The blueprint defines *what a house will have* (rooms, doors, windows → **attributes**) and *what it can do* (open door, switch on light → **methods**).

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Analogy Mapping:**
> `Blueprint  =  Class`
> `Actual House built from it  =  Object`
> `Material of the house (bricks, cement)  =  Instance Variables (state)`
> `Actions (open door, lock)  =  Methods (behaviour)`

### 1.3 Why Classes? – The "Why" Behind OOP

Before OOP, **procedural languages** (C, Pascal) treated data and functions as separate entities. As programs grew, this caused:

- **Data insecurity** (any function could corrupt any data).
- **Poor modularity** (a change in one function could ripple through the whole program).
- **No real-world mapping** (a "Student" could not be modelled as a single, secure unit).

A **class** solves all three by **binding data + behaviour together** and **hiding** the internal details (Encapsulation).

> [!TIP]
> **Remember for KTU viva:** A class is a **logical entity** — it has no physical existence in memory until an object is created. Memory is allocated only when `new` is invoked.

### 1.4 Components of a Class (At a Glance)

| Component | Purpose | Example |
|---|---|---|
| **Fields / Attributes** | Store the state of an object | `String name;` |
| **Methods** | Define behaviour | `void study() { }` |
| **Constructors** | Initialise new objects | `Student() { }` |
| **Access Modifiers** | Control visibility | `public`, `private` |
| **`this` keyword** | Refers to current object | `this.name = name;` |

---

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Anatomy of a Java Class – Structured Logic Breakdown

A class declaration in Java follows a precise, mandatory syntactic structure. Let us break each part of the structure into the "Why" and "How".

#### A. Class Declaration Syntax

```java
[access_modifier] [non_access_modifier] class ClassName {
    // 1. Fields (state)
    // 2. Constructors (initialisation)
    // 3. Methods (behaviour)
    // 4. Nested classes / interfaces (optional)
}
```

| Part | Mandatory? | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `access_modifier` | Optional | Visibility of the class (`public` or default/package-private) |
| `non_access_modifier` | Optional | `final`, `abstract`, `static` |
| `class` keyword | **Mandatory** | Tells the compiler "I am defining a class" |
| `ClassName` | **Mandatory** | Must be a valid Java identifier, **PascalCase** convention |
| `{ }` body | **Mandatory** | Contains members |

> [!NOTE]
> **Filename Rule (KTU favourite trick question):** If a class is declared `public`, the file **MUST** be named `ClassName.java`. The compiler enforces this strictly. If the class is non-public, filename can differ.

#### B. Fields (Instance Variables)

**Why?** Fields hold the *unique state* of each object. If 100 students are created, each has its **own copy** of `name`, `rollNo`, `marks`.

**How?**
- Declared inside a class but **outside any method**.
- Get a default value if not initialised explicitly (`0`, `0.0`, `false`, `null`).
- Accessed using the dot operator: `object.field`.

#### C. Methods (Member Functions)

**Why?** Methods define *what the object can do*. They are the verbs of the class.

**How?**
- Can be **instance methods** (need an object) or **static methods** (belong to the class).
- May or may not return a value.
- Can accept **parameters** (primitive or reference types).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **`void` vs Return Type:** If a method declares a return type (e.g., `int`), it **must** use `return` keyword. A `void` method cannot return a value but may use `return;` to exit early.

#### D. Constructors

**Why?** To guarantee that an object is **born in a valid state**. Java does not allow uninitialised objects for user-defined classes.

**How?**
- Same name as the class, **no return type** (not even `void`).
- Called automatically when `new` is used.
- If you write no constructor, Java provides a **default no-arg constructor**.

#### E. The `this` Keyword

**Why?** To remove ambiguity when instance variable and parameter share the same name.

**How?**
- `this` refers to the **current invoking object**.
- `this.x = x;` means "assign parameter `x` to the current object's field `x`".

### 2.2 KTU High-Yield Formula / Cheat Sheet

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Master this table — every cell is a potential KTU 2-mark or 5-mark question.**

| Concept | Syntax Rule | Memory / Behaviour | Default Value |
|---|---|---|---|
| Class declaration | `class Student { }` | Logical entity, no memory allocated | — |
| Object creation | `Student s1 = new Student();` | Memory allocated on **heap** | — |
| Field | `int age;` | One copy per object (instance) | `0` |
| Local variable | `int x = 10;` (inside method) | On **stack**, must be initialised before use | **No default** |
| Static field | `static int count;` | **One** copy per class, shared across objects | `0` |
| Method | `void display() { }` | Must be inside a class | — |
| Constructor | `Student() { }` | Auto-invoked by `new` | — |
| Access: `public` | Visible to **all** classes | Everywhere | — |
| Access: `private` | Visible **only inside** same class | Encapsulation | — |
| Access: `protected` | Same package + subclasses | Inheritance support | — |
| Access: *default* (no keyword) | Same package only | Package-private | — |
| `this` keyword | `this.field` | Refers to current object | — |
| `new` keyword | `new ClassName()` | Allocates heap memory & returns reference | — |

### 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Modelling IoT Devices:** Class `Sensor` with fields `temperature`, `humidity` and method `readData()`.
- **Banking Software:** Class `Account` encapsulates `balance` (private) and provides `deposit()`, `withdraw()` (public).
- **Simulation Systems:** Class `Robot` with attributes like `x`, `y` position and methods like `move()`, `rotate()`.
- **GUI Applications:** Each Swing/JavaFX window is essentially a class extending `JFrame`.

> [!TIP]
> **KTU 2024 Scheme emphasis:** Questions on **access modifiers** and **constructor overloading** are the highest-weightage topics in this module. Always draw a small diagram showing visibility scope in your answer.

---

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Exhaustive Walkthrough – Building a Class from Scratch

Let us derive a complete, KTU-examination-ready Java class **step-by-step**, explaining every transition.

#### Step 1: Identify the Real-World Entity
Suppose we need to model a **Student** for a university record system. The class should hold:
- *Attributes:* `name` (String), `rollNo` (int), `cgpa` (double)
- *Behaviour:* `display()`, `isEligible()` (checks `cgpa >= 6.0`)

#### Step 2: Apply Access Modifiers (Encapsulation Rule)
By KTU/OOP best practice, **all fields must be `private`** and accessed through **public getters/setters**. This is the **Encapsulation principle**.

```java
class Student {
    private String name;
    private int rollNo;
    private double cgpa;
}
```

> **Logic:** `private` ensures no outside class can directly corrupt the data. Only methods of `Student` itself can touch it.

#### Step 3: Add Constructors (Initialisation Logic)
We provide a **parameterised constructor** and a **no-arg constructor** (constructor overloading).

```java
class Student {
    private String name;
    private int rollNo;
    private double cgpa;

    // No-arg constructor
    public Student() {
        this.name = "Unknown";
        this.rollNo = 0;
        this.cgpa = 0.0;
    }

    // Parameterised constructor
    public Student(String name, int rollNo, double cgpa) {
        this.name = name;     // 'this.name' = field, 'name' = parameter
        this.rollNo = rollNo;
        this.cgpa = cgpa;
    }
}
```

**Why two constructors?** To allow flexible object creation:
- `new Student()` → creates a default student.
- `new Student("Anu", 42, 8.7)` → creates a specific student.

#### Step 4: Add Behaviour (Methods)

```java
class Student {
    private String name;
    private int rollNo;
    private double cgpa;

    public Student() {
        this("Unknown", 0, 0.0);   // constructor chaining
    }

    public Student(String name, int rollNo, double cgpa) {
        this.name = name;
        this.rollNo = rollNo;
        this.cgpa = cgpa;
    }

    // Getter
    public String getName() {
        return this.name;
    }

    // Setter (with validation - KTU favourite)
    public void setCgpa(double cgpa) {
        if (cgpa >= 0.0 && cgpa <= 10.0) {
            this.cgpa = cgpa;
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid CGPA");
        }
    }

    // Behaviour method
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Name : " + this.name);
        System.out.println("Roll : " + this.rollNo);
        System.out.println("CGPA : " + this.cgpa);
    }

    // Business logic method
    public boolean isEligible() {
        return this.cgpa >= 6.0;
    }
}
```

#### Step 5: Create Objects and Invoke Behaviour

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Object 1
        Student s1 = new Student("Ananya", 101, 8.5);

        // Object 2
        Student s2 = new Student();
        s2.setCgpa(7.2);

        s1.display();
        System.out.println("Eligible? " + s1.isEligible());

        s2.display();
        System.out.println("Eligible? " + s2.isEligible());
    }
}
```

#### Step 6: Trace the Output

| Statement | `s1` state | `s2` state |
|---|---|---|
| `new Student("Ananya", 101, 8.5)` | name=Ananya, roll=101, cgpa=8.5 | (not yet created) |
| `new Student()` | unchanged | name=Unknown, roll=0, cgpa=0.0 |
| `s2.setCgpa(7.2)` | unchanged | cgpa becomes 7.2 |
| `s1.display()` | Prints Ananya's record | — |
| `s2.isEligible()` | — | Returns `true` (7.2 ≥ 6.0) |

### 3.2 Analytical Matrix – Difference Between Class & Object

| Parameter | Class | Object |
|---|---|---|
| Definition | Blueprint/template | Instance of class |
| Keyword | `class` | `new` |
| Memory | **No** memory allocated | Memory allocated on **heap** |
| Declaration | Declared once | Can be created many times |
| Existence | Logical | Physical (in memory at runtime) |
| Example | `Student` | `s1`, `s2`, `s3` … |

### 3.3 Step-by-Step: How Memory is Allocated

1. Compiler reads `Student s1;` → **reference variable `s1` is created on the stack**, value is `null`.
2. `new Student("Ananya", 101, 8.5);` → JVM allocates memory on **heap** for all instance variables.
3. Constructor runs → fields are initialised with passed values.
4. The heap address is assigned to `s1`. Now `s1` points to the object.
5. `s1.display()` → JVM follows the reference, finds the object, and executes the method.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Hot Topic:** "What is the difference between a *reference variable* and an *object*?" — Answer: A reference is a *pointer* stored on the **stack**; the actual object lives on the **heap**.

---

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

