## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, Model Paper – Set B]`**
**Define a class in Java. How is it different from an object? Illustrate with an example.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

A **class** in Java is a user-defined blueprint that encapsulates data (fields) and behaviour (methods) into a single logical unit. It is declared using the `class` keyword. An **object** is a runtime instance of a class, created using the `new` keyword, occupying memory on the heap.

| Class | Object |
|---|---|
| Logical template | Physical instance |
| No memory at declaration | Memory allocated on heap |
| Declared once | Many instances possible |

```java
class Car {                 // Class
    String model;
    void drive() { }
}
Car c = new Car();          // Object
```

> Here `Car` is the class, `c` is the object.

---

**Q2. `[KTU University Exam – May 2024, Module 2, PYQ Pattern]`**
**Explain the role of access modifiers in Java. List the four access levels with their visibility scope.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

Access modifiers in Java control the **visibility** (who can access) of classes, methods, and fields. They are central to **Encapsulation**, one of the four pillars of OOP.

| Modifier | Same Class | Same Package | Subclass (other pkg) | Other Packages |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `private` | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| `default` | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ |
| `protected` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ |
| `public` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |

In KTU Module 2 context, **all data members are declared `private`** and accessed through **public getters/setters** to enforce encapsulation.

---

### 5.2 Part B — 14-Mark Questions (Module Internal Choice)

---

### **Question A `[KTU University Exam – Model Paper 2024 Scheme, Module 2]`**

**(a) [7 marks]** Explain the general structure of a Java class. Write a complete Java program to define a class `Employee` with private data members `empId`, `name`, and `salary`. Provide a parameterised constructor, a method `display()`, and a method `isHighEarner()` that returns `true` if salary > 50,000.

**(b) [7 marks]** Discuss the concept of constructors in Java. Explain constructor overloading with a suitable example. What is a *default constructor* and when is it provided by the compiler?

---

#### **Solution to Q.A (a):**

**General structure of a Java class:**

A Java class contains four major parts — (1) **access modifier**, (2) **class keyword and class name**, (3) **fields (state)**, (4) **methods (behaviour)** and optionally **constructors**.

```java
[access_modifier] class ClassName {
    // Fields
    // Constructors
    // Methods
}
```

**Complete Java Program:**

```java
class Employee {
    private int empId;
    private String name;
    private double salary;

    // Parameterised constructor
    public Employee(int empId, String name, double salary) {
        this.empId = empId;
        this.name  = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Employee ID : " + this.empId);
        System.out.println("Name        : " + this.name);
        System.out.println("Salary      : " + this.salary);
    }

    public boolean isHighEarner() {
        return this.salary > 50000;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee e1 = new Employee(201, "Rahul", 65000);
        Employee e2 = new Employee(202, "Meera", 42000);

        e1.display();
        System.out.println("High earner? " + e1.isHighEarner());

        System.out.println("---");

        e2.display();
        System.out.println("High earner? " + e2.isHighEarner());
    }
}
```

**Output Trace:**

| Object | Salary | `isHighEarner()` |
|---|---|---|
| `e1` (Rahul) | 65000 | `true` |
| `e2` (Meera) | 42000 | `false` |

---

#### **Solution to Q.A (b):**

A **constructor** in Java is a **special member** used to **initialise** an object. It has the following properties:

1. **Same name** as the class.
2. **No return type** (not even `void`).
3. Called **automatically** when `new` is used.
4. If no constructor is written, Java inserts a **default no-arg constructor**.

**Constructor Overloading** = defining **multiple constructors** with different parameter lists within the same class. The compiler differentiates them by the **signature** (number/type of parameters).

```java
class Box {
    double length, width, height;

    // Constructor 1
    Box() {
        this.length = this.width = this.height = 0;
    }

    // Constructor 2
    Box(double side) {
        this.length = this.width = this.height = side;
    }

    // Constructor 3
    Box(double l, double w, double h) {
        this.length = l;
        this.width  = w;
        this.height = h;
    }

    double volume() {
        return this.length * this.width * this.height;
    }
}
```

**Default Constructor:**
- Provided **automatically by the compiler** if the programmer defines **no constructor** at all.
- It is a **no-arg, public** constructor whose body is empty.
- It is **NOT** provided if the programmer writes even a single constructor.

```java
class A { }                      // Compiler adds A() { }
class B { B(int x) { } }         // No default constructor; new A() will FAIL
```

---

### **Question B `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2024 Model Paper, Module 2, Alternative Choice]`**

**(a) [7 marks]** What is the significance of the `this` keyword in Java? With a neat diagram and program, explain how multiple objects of the same class have **independent copies** of instance variables.

**(b) [7 marks]** Compare **instance variables vs static variables** and **instance methods vs static methods** in Java. Write a Java program to maintain a `count` of objects created using a `static` variable.

---

#### **Solution to Q.B (a):**

The **`this` keyword** in Java refers to the **current invoking object**. It is mainly used:

1. To **differentiate** between instance variables and parameters with the same name.
2. To **pass the current object** as a parameter to another method.
3. To invoke one constructor from another (**constructor chaining**): `this()`.

**Demonstrating Independent Copies of Instance Variables:**

```java
class Counter {
    int count;          // instance variable - each object has its own copy

    Counter(int c) {
        this.count = c;   // 'this.count' = object's field
    }

    void increment() {
        this.count++;
    }

    void show() {
        System.out.println("Count = " + this.count);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Counter a = new Counter(10);
        Counter b = new Counter(20);

        a.increment();   // only a's count changes
        a.increment();

        b.increment();

        a.show();   // 12
        b.show();   // 21
    }
}
```

**Memory Diagram:**

```mermaid
graph LR
    A["Stack: a"] -->|ref 0x100| A1["Heap: a.count = 12"]
    B["Stack: b"] -->|ref 0x200| B1["Heap: b.count = 21"]
```

Each object gets its **own** copy on the heap, proving that instance variables are not shared.

---

#### **Solution to Q.B (b):**

| Parameter | Instance Variable | Static Variable |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword | None | `static` |
| Copies | One per object | **One per class** (shared) |
| Memory | Allocated when `new` is used | Allocated when class is loaded |
| Access | Through object | Through class name (recommended) |

| Parameter | Instance Method | Static Method |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword | None | `static` |
| Can access instance vars? | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (must use object) |
| Called via | `obj.method()` | `ClassName.method()` |
| `this` allowed? | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |

**Java Program: Counting Objects with `static`:**

```java
class Student {
    private String name;
    static int objectCount = 0;     // shared across all objects

    public Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        objectCount++;              // increment on every creation
    }

    public static int getObjectCount() {
        return objectCount;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student("Anu");
        Student s2 = new Student("Ravi");
        Student s3 = new Student("Meera");

        System.out.println("Total students created: " +
                            Student.getObjectCount());
    }
}
```

**Output:** `Total students created: 3`

> Here `objectCount` is shared — all three constructors increment the **same** memory location. This is a classic KTU question on the `static` keyword.

---

### 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Pitfalls — Where KTU Students Lose Marks:**
>
> 1. **Confusing `void` with no return type in constructors.** A constructor MUST NOT have a return type, not even `void`. (–1 mark)
> 2. **Forgetting `this.`** when parameter name = field name. Without `this`, the assignment becomes a *no-op*. (–1 mark)
> 3. **Declaring fields as `public`.** KTU strictly expects **encapsulation** — fields `private`, methods `public`. (–1 to –2 marks)
> 4. **Not writing the filename match rule** for public classes. (–1 mark)
> 5. **Confusing *default constructor* (compiler-generated, no-arg)** with *no-arg constructor* (programmer-written, can have a body).
> 6. **In object-creation questions, students often forget the `new` keyword**, writing `Student s1 = Student();` — this is a **compilation error**.
> 7. **Missing the static vs instance distinction** in part (b) questions — always draw a memory diagram to be safe.

---

### 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- A **class** is a *blueprint*, an **object** is a *real instance* — never confuse the two.
- The `new` keyword is **mandatory** to create an object; it allocates memory on the **heap**.
- **Encapsulation** = `private` fields + `public` getters/setters — the KTU gold standard.
- **Constructors** have the class name and **no return type**; if you write one, the compiler-supplied default constructor is removed.
- **`this`** refers to the *current object*; it is used to disambiguate field vs parameter.
- **Instance variables** = one per object; **static variables** = one per class (shared).
- **Instance methods** can use `this` and access instance fields; **static methods** cannot.
- File name **must match** the `public` class name — `ClassName.java`.
- A Java file can have **only one** `public` class, but **any number** of non-public classes.
- For KTU answer sheets, **always draw a memory diagram** (Stack vs Heap) — it earns easy bonus marks.

> [!TIP]
> **Last-minute revision mantra:** *"Class = Plan, Object = Product, Constructor = Birth, `this` = Identity, `private` = Safety, `static` = Shared."*

---

