# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

**Method Overriding** is a fundamental feature of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) that allows a **subclass (child class)** to provide a **specific implementation** of a method that is **already defined** in its **superclass (parent class)**. The overridden method in the child class must have the **same name**, **same return type** (or covariant return type), and **same parameter list** as the method in the parent class.

In the KTU 2024 syllabus context (PEMRT415 - OOP, Module 2: Inheritance and Polymorphism), method overriding is the **runtime polymorphism mechanism** that enables **dynamic method dispatch**, where the JVM decides at runtime which version of the method to invoke based on the actual object type, not the reference type.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition:** *"Method overriding occurs when a subclass redefines a method inherited from its superclass using the exact same method signature, enabling runtime polymorphism through dynamic method dispatch."*

The KTU examiner specifically tests whether students understand:
- The **difference between Overloading (compile-time)** and **Overriding (runtime)**.
- The role of the **`@Override` annotation** in Java.
- The use of **`super` keyword** to call the parent's overridden method.
- The concept of **Dynamic Method Dispatch** (Late Binding).
- **Access modifier rules** during overriding.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine a **generic form/template** at a company — a standard "Employee Bio" form that everyone fills out with basic fields like Name, ID, and Date of Joining. This is the **parent class method**.

Now, when a **Software Engineer** fills the form, they add extra technical skills. When a **Sales Manager** fills it, they add client-handling experience. Each specialized role **overrides** the generic bio with their **own specialized version**, but the **form's structure (signature)** remains the same.

In technical terms:
- The **Employee Bio form** → `displayDetails()` method in the **Parent class (Employee)**.
- The **Software Engineer's specialized bio** → `displayDetails()` method in the **Child class (SoftwareEngineer)**.
- The **HR department** (JVM) decides at the **time of submission** (runtime) which version of the bio to display based on the **actual person** (object) submitting it.

> [!NOTE]
> **Plain English Summary:** Method overriding is like a child "redoing" a parent's homework in their own style, but keeping the same question and structure. The teacher (JVM) grades whichever version the child actually submits at the time of evaluation (runtime).

## 1.3 Key Terminology at a Glance

| Term | Meaning | KTU Significance |
|------|---------|------------------|
| **Method Signature** | Method name + parameter list (not return type) | Must be **identical** for valid overriding |
| **Dynamic Method Dispatch** | Runtime decision of which method to call | Core concept tested in 14-mark questions |
| **`super` keyword** | Refers to the immediate parent class | Used to call parent's overridden version |
| **`@Override` annotation** | Compile-time check marker in Java | Ensures method actually overrides something |
| **Covariant Return Type** | Return type can be a subclass of parent's return type | Allowed only in Java 5+ |

## 1.4 Mathematical Representation of Overriding Signature Rule

For a valid override, the following must hold for a method `m` in class `B` (subclass) overriding method `m` in class `A` (superclass):

$$ \text{Signature}(m_B) \equiv \text{Signature}(m_A) $$

$$ \text{Name}(m_B) = \text{Name}(m_A) \land \text{Parameters}(m_B) = \text{Parameters}(m_A) $$

$$ \text{ReturnType}(m_B) \preceq \text{ReturnType}(m_A) \quad \text{(Covariant or same)} $$

$$ \text{Access}(m_B) \succeq \text{Access}(m_A) \quad \text{(Cannot reduce visibility)} $$

Where $\preceq$ denotes "is a subtype of" and $\succeq$ denotes "equal or higher visibility level."

