# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Complete Worked Example: Step-by-Step Analysis

Let us consider a classic KTU-style problem to demonstrate method overriding with full traceability.

### Java Code: The Vehicle Hierarchy

```java
// Parent Class
class Vehicle {
    String brand;
    int speed;

    Vehicle(String brand, int speed) {
        this.brand = brand;
        this.speed = speed;
    }

    // Method to be overridden
    void displayInfo() {
        System.out.println("Brand: " + brand);
        System.out.println("Speed: " + speed + " km/h");
    }

    void start() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle is starting...");
    }
}

// Child Class 1
class Car extends Vehicle {
    int numDoors;

    Car(String brand, int speed, int numDoors) {
        super(brand, speed);
        this.numDoors = numDoors;
    }

    @Override
    void displayInfo() {
        super.displayInfo();  // Calls parent's version
        System.out.println("Number of Doors: " + numDoors);
        System.out.println("Type: Car");
    }

    @Override
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Car engine is starting with a key turn...");
    }
}

// Child Class 2
class Motorcycle extends Vehicle {
    boolean hasSidecar;

    Motorcycle(String brand, int speed, boolean hasSidecar) {
        super(brand, speed);
        this.hasSidecar = hasSidecar;
    }

    @Override
    void displayInfo() {
        super.displayInfo();
        System.out.println("Has Sidecar: " + hasSidecar);
        System.out.println("Type: Motorcycle");
    }

    @Override
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Motorcycle is kick-started...");
    }
}
```

### Driver Class Demonstrating Runtime Polymorphism

```java
public class OverridingDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Parent reference, child objects - THE KEY TO RUNTIME POLYMORPHISM
        Vehicle v1 = new Car("Toyota", 180, 4);
        Vehicle v2 = new Motorcycle("Harley", 120, false);

        System.out.println("=== Vehicle 1 Info ===");
        v1.displayInfo();  // Calls Car's version
        v1.start();        // Calls Car's version

        System.out.println("\n=== Vehicle 2 Info ===");
        v2.displayInfo();  // Calls Motorcycle's version
        v2.start();        // Calls Motorcycle's version
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Execution Trace

Let us trace the execution of `v1.displayInfo()` to understand dynamic dispatch:

**Step 1:** The compiler sees `v1` declared as type `Vehicle`. The compiler **checks** if `Vehicle` has a method `displayInfo()`. It does. **Compilation succeeds.**

**Step 2:** At runtime, the JVM looks at the **actual object** that `v1` points to. It is a `Car` object.

**Step 3:** The JVM checks the `Car` class's vtable. It finds `displayInfo()` is **overridden** in `Car`.

**Step 4:** The JVM invokes `Car.displayInfo()`, not `Vehicle.displayInfo()`.

**Step 5:** Inside `Car.displayInfo()`, the first line is `super.displayInfo()`. The JVM now **explicitly** calls the parent's version.

**Step 6:** The `Car` version continues to print the additional fields and returns.

This can be summarized as:

$$ \text{Call}(v_1.\text{displayInfo}()) = \text{Lookup}(\text{ActualType}(v_1), \text{displayInfo}) $$

$$ = \text{Lookup}(\text{Car}, \text{displayInfo}) = \text{Car.displayInfo}() $$

$$ \text{Which internally executes: } \text{super.displayInfo}() \rightarrow \text{Vehicle.displayInfo}() $$

## 3.2 Analytical Matrix: Overriding vs. Overloading

This is the **single most important comparison** for KTU exams. The examiner will test this in either a 3-mark or 14-mark question.

| Comparison Parameter | Method Overriding | Method Overloading |
|----------------------|-------------------|-------------------|
| **Definition** | Redefining parent class method in child class | Defining multiple methods with same name but different signatures in same class |
| **Class Relationship** | Requires inheritance (IS-A relationship) | Can be in same class or across inherited classes |
| **Method Signature** | Must be **identical** | Must be **different** (params/type/order) |
| **Return Type** | Same or covariant | Can be different (no restriction) |
| **Binding Type** | **Runtime (Late Binding / Dynamic)** | **Compile-time (Early Binding / Static)** |
| **Polymorphism Type** | **Runtime Polymorphism** | **Compile-time Polymorphism** |
| **Access Modifiers** | Cannot reduce visibility | No restriction |
| **Exception Rules** | Cannot throw new/broader checked exceptions | No restriction |
| **`@Override` annotation** | Strongly recommended | Not applicable (causes compile error) |
| **Performance** | Slightly slower (vtable lookup) | Faster (resolved at compile time) |
| **Examples** | `Car.start()` overrides `Vehicle.start()` | `add(int a, int b)` and `add(double a, double b)` |
| **Achieved via** | Inheritance | Method name reuse with different parameters |

## 3.3 Validating the Overriding Rules — Edge Cases

### Case 1: Covariant Return Type (Valid)

```java
class Animal {
    Animal reproduce() { return new Animal(); }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    Dog reproduce() { return new Dog(); }  // Valid: Dog IS-A Animal
}
```

**Rule applied:** $\text{ReturnType}(Dog) \preceq \text{ReturnType}(Animal)$. Since $Dog$ extends $Animal$, this is a **covariant return type** and is **valid**.

### Case 2: Widening Access Modifier (Valid)

```java
class Parent {
    protected void show() { System.out.println("Parent"); }
}
class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    public void show() { System.out.println("Child"); }  // Valid: protected -> public
}
```

**Rule applied:** $V_{child} = \text{public} > V_{parent} = \text{protected}$. Visibility is **widened**, which is allowed.

### Case 3: Narrowing Access Modifier (Invalid)

```java
class Parent {
    public void show() { System.out.println("Parent"); }
}
class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    private void show() { System.out.println("Child"); }  // COMPILE ERROR
}
```

**Rule applied:** $V_{child} = \text{private} < V_{parent} = \text{public}$. This **violates the access modifier rule** and results in a compile-time error: *"attempting to assign weaker access privileges; was public"*.

### Case 4: Method Hiding with `static` (NOT Overriding)

```java
class Parent {
    static void display() { System.out.println("Parent static"); }
}
class Child extends Parent {
    static void display() { System.out.println("Child static"); }  // Method hiding, NOT overriding
}
```

**Rule applied:** Static methods are resolved at **compile-time** based on the **reference type**, not the object type. This is a famous KTU trick — static methods **hide** rather than override.

### Case 5: Exception Reduction (Valid)

```java
import java.io.*;
class Parent {
    void read() throws IOException { /* ... */ }
}
class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    void read() throws FileNotFoundException { /* ... */ }  // Valid: narrower exception
}
```

**Rule applied:** $E_{child} = \{\text{FileNotFoundException}\} \subset E_{parent} = \{\text{IOException}\}$. This is **narrowing** and is **valid**.

### Case 6: Exception Escalation (Invalid)

```java
import java.io.*;
class Parent {
    void read() { /* ... */ }
}
class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    void read() throws IOException { /* ... */ }  // COMPILE ERROR: new checked exception
}
```

**Rule applied:** $E_{child} = \{\text{IOException}\} \not\subset E_{parent} = \emptyset$. This **violates the exception rule** and is **invalid**.

## 3.4 The Method Resolution Algorithm (Conceptual Flow)

When the JVM encounters `obj.method(args)`, it executes the following algorithm:

1. **Compile-time check:** Verify that the **declared type** of `obj` declares or inherits a method matching the signature. If not, **compile error**.
2. **Runtime lookup:** Find the **actual class** of the object referenced by `obj`.
3. **vtable search:** Search the actual class's method table for an exact signature match. If found, invoke it.
4. **Inheritance walk:** If not found, walk up the class hierarchy to the parent class and repeat step 3.
5. **Invoke:** Execute the matched method body.

This algorithm is what makes overriding achieve **dynamic dispatch**.

