# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1: Conceptual Definition
**Q: Define method overriding. How is it different from method overloading?** `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**Model Answer:**

**Method Overriding** is the OOP feature that allows a subclass to provide a specific implementation of a method that is already defined in its superclass. The overriding method must have the **same name**, **same parameter list**, and **same or covariant return type** as the parent's method. It enables **runtime polymorphism** through dynamic method dispatch.

**Key Differences from Overloading:**

| Aspect | Overriding | Overloading |
|--------|------------|-------------|
| Signature | Must be **identical** | Must be **different** |
| Classes | Across **parent-child** | Within the **same class** (or inherited) |
| Binding | **Runtime** (Dynamic) | **Compile-time** (Static) |
| Polymorphism | Runtime polymorphism | Compile-time polymorphism |

### Question 2: Access Modifier Rule
**Q: Can a subclass override a `public` method of the superclass as `private`? Justify your answer.** `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Model Answer:**

**No**, a subclass **cannot** override a `public` method of the superclass as `private`. This violates the **access modifier rule of method overriding**, which states that the overriding method in the subclass must have **equal or wider visibility** than the method in the superclass. Visibility levels in increasing order are: `private < default < protected < public`.

If attempted, the Java compiler throws a compile-time error: *"attempting to assign weaker access privileges; was public"*. For example, if `Parent` declares `public void show()` and `Child` attempts `private void show()`, compilation fails. This rule ensures that the **contract** of the parent class is never weakened by the subclass, preserving the **Liskov Substitution Principle**.

