> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout:**
> 
> **Common Mistakes Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 
> 1. **Confusing Overriding with Overloading (3-5 marks lost):** Students often write "method overriding is when we have multiple methods with different parameters." This is WRONG. Overriding = same signature, Overloading = different signature.
> 
> 2. **Forgetting the Access Modifier Rule (2 marks lost):** Many students believe any method can be overridden with any access modifier. Always state the visibility hierarchy: `private < default < protected < public`.
> 
> 3. **Claiming `static` methods can be overridden (2 marks lost):** This is a classic trap. Static methods are **hidden**, not overridden. The KTU key explicitly penalizes this.
> 
> 4. **Ignoring the Exception Rule (1-2 marks lost):** When a 14-mark question involves overriding, you must mention that **new checked exceptions cannot be thrown**.
> 
> 5. **Not mentioning Dynamic Method Dispatch (1-2 marks lost):** If the question asks about "runtime polymorphism," you **must** use the exact term "Dynamic Method Dispatch" and explain the vtable mechanism.
> 
> 6. **Writing code without explanation (3-4 marks lost):** A 14-mark question expects both code AND a conceptual explanation. Code alone is worth at most 5-6 marks.
> 
> 7. **Missing the `@Override` annotation:** While not strictly required, omitting it in exam code shows incomplete understanding and may cost ½ to 1 mark.
> 
> 8. **Forgetting to mention that the return type can be covariant:** Many students write "return type must be the same" which is technically incomplete. Use the phrase "same or covariant return type."

