## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **High-Density Revision Checklist — Method Overriding**

- **Definition:** Subclass provides a **specific implementation** of a method already defined in the superclass with the **same name, same parameters**.

- **Signature Rule:** Method name + parameter list must be **IDENTICAL**. Return type can be the **same or covariant**.

- **Access Rule:** Visibility **cannot be reduced**. Hierarchy: `private < default < protected < public`.

- **Exception Rule:** Cannot throw **new or broader checked exceptions**. Unchecked exceptions have no restriction.

- **`final` methods:** **Cannot be overridden** (sealed by parent).

- **`static` methods:** **Hidden, not overridden** (resolved at compile-time).

- **Constructors:** **Not inherited**, so they cannot be overridden. Use `super()` for chaining.

- **Private methods:** **Not inherited**, so a same-named method in the child is a **new method**, not an override.

- **`@Override` annotation:** **Compile-time safety check**. Always use it in exam code.

- **`super` keyword:** Used to call the **parent's overridden version** from within the child's version: `super.methodName()`.

- **Dynamic Method Dispatch:** The JVM determines which method to invoke at **runtime** based on the **actual object type**, not the reference type. This is achieved through the **vtable** (method table) mechanism.

- **Runtime Polymorphism:** Method overriding is the **mechanism** that enables **runtime polymorphism**. Always mention both terms together in answers.

- **Reference Type vs Object Type:** Compile-time check uses **reference type**. Runtime dispatch uses **object type**. This distinction is critical.

- **Performance:** Overriding has a **slight runtime overhead** due to vtable lookup, but enables powerful polymorphism.

- **Open/Closed Principle:** Method overriding supports the OOP principle that classes should be **open for extension but closed for modification**.

- **Liskov Substitution Principle:** Any overridden method must **strengthen, not weaken**, the parent's contract (hence the access and exception rules).

- **Java-Specific:** Java 5+ supports **covariant return types**. Java does not support **covariant parameter types** (that would be overloading).

- **KTU Exam Frequency:** This topic appears in **every KTU OOP exam**, typically as a 7-mark or 14-mark question in Module 2.

- **Practical Lab:** You will be asked to write programs demonstrating overriding with shapes, vehicles, employees, animals, or bank accounts. Practice at least 3 such hierarchies.

- **Difference from Abstract Methods:** Overriding is **optional refinement** of a concrete method. Abstract methods **must** be overridden (mandatory implementation).

