# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Notes

## 2.1 The `final` Keyword — Three Application Modes

### 2.1.1 `final` Variables (Constants)

A `final` variable can be assigned **exactly once**. There are three flavours:

**a) Local final variable** — declared inside a method/block:

```java
void calculate() {
    final double PI = 3.14159;   // cannot be reassigned later
    // PI = 3.14;  // COMPILE-TIME ERROR
}
```

**b) Instance final variable** — declared in a class, *must* be initialized:
- At the time of declaration, **OR**
- Inside every constructor of the class.

```java
class Employee {
    final String empId;        // blank final
    Employee(String id) {
        this.empId = id;       // initialized in constructor
    }
}
```

**c) Static final variable (Class constant)** — declared `static final`:

```java
class MathConstants {
    public static final double PI = 3.14159;
    public static final int MAX_USERS = 100;
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield:** Naming convention for `static final` constants is **ALL_UPPER_SNAKE_CASE** with underscores separating words.

### 2.1.2 `final` Methods (No Overriding)

When a method is declared `final`, no subclass can provide a *new implementation* (override) for it. This is a **performance optimization** — the JVM knows the call cannot be polymorphic, so it can perform **inlining** at compile time.

```java
class Parent {
    final void display() {
        System.out.println("Parent's final method");
    }
}
class Child extends Parent {
    // void display() { ... }  // COMPILE-TIME ERROR: cannot override final
}
```

### 2.1.3 `final` Classes (No Inheritance)

When a class is declared `final`, it **cannot be subclassed**. The most famous example is `java.lang.String` — making `String` `final` ensures:
- **Security** — no malicious subclass can mimic `String` and bypass security checks.
- **Immutability** — guaranteed thread-safety and caching.
- **Performance** — JIT optimizations are safe to apply.

```java
final class ImmutablePoint {
    private final int x, y;
    ImmutablePoint(int x, int y) { this.x = x; this.y = y; }
}
// class SubPoint extends ImmutablePoint { }   // ERROR
```

### 2.1.4 `final` Parameters

A method parameter declared `final` cannot be modified inside the method. This is commonly used in **inner classes** and **anonymous classes** which can only access `final` local variables.

```java
void process(final int value) {
    // value = value + 1;  // ERROR: cannot reassign
    System.out.println(value);
}
```

