## 2.2 Packages — Deep Dive

### 2.2.1 Package Naming Convention

Java packages follow a **reverse domain naming convention** to ensure global uniqueness:

```
com.company.project.module
in.ac.ktu.department.course
org.apache.commons.lang
```

- All **lowercase** letters.
- Hierarchical, separated by dots (which mirror folder structure on disk).
- Reserved prefixes: `java.*`, `javax.*` are reserved for the Java platform.

### 2.2.2 Types of Packages

| Type | Examples | Description |
|---|---|---|
| **Built-in (Java API)** | `java.lang`, `java.util`, `java.io`, `java.net` | Pre-shipped with JDK |
| **User-defined** | `com.ktu.banking` | Created by the developer |
| **Nested (Sub-packages)** | `java.util.regex` | A package inside another package |

> [!NOTE]
> `java.lang` is auto-imported by the compiler. You never write `import java.lang.String;`.

### 2.2.3 The `import` Statement

Two main forms:
```java
import java.util.ArrayList;       // specific class import
import java.util.*;               // wildcard — imports all classes
```

**Implicit (default) import:**
```java
import java.lang.*;   // automatically inserted by compiler
```

**Static import** (used for constants):
```java
import static java.lang.Math.PI;
import static java.lang.System.out;
```

### 2.2.4 CLASSPATH and JAR Files

The **CLASSPATH** is an environment variable (or command-line argument) that tells the JVM where to look for user-defined packages. Packages physically correspond to **directories** on the filesystem (or entries inside a **JAR** — Java ARchive file).

```
D:\myproject\classes\com\ktu\banking\Account.class
       ↑      ↑                                ↑
  CLASSPATH root   package structure   .class file
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Tip:** When asked "How does the compiler locate classes?", the answer is: **CLASSPATH** + **fully qualified class name** = location on disk.

### 2.2.5 Access Control Across Packages

The four access levels ordered from most to least restrictive:

| Modifier | Same Class | Same Package | Subclass (different pkg) | Other Packages |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `private` | ✓ | ✗ | ✗ | ✗ |
| *(default)* package-private | ✓ | ✓ | ✗ | ✗ |
| `protected` | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✗ |
| `public` | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Pitfall:** Students often confuse `default` access with `protected`. Default = same package only. Protected = same package **OR** any subclass (even in a different package).

---

## 2.3 Interfaces — Deep Dive

### 2.3.1 Interface Declaration Rules

From Java 8 onwards, an interface may contain:
- **Constants** → implicitly `public static final`
- **Abstract methods** → implicitly `public abstract`
- **Default methods** → `default` keyword, has a body
- **Static methods** → `static` keyword, has a body
- **Nested classes/interfaces** → implicitly `public static`

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Pre-Java 8 interfaces could contain only public static final fields and public abstract methods.** This is a *high-frequency KTU question*.

### 2.3.2 Abstract Methods in Interfaces

```java
public interface Shape {
    double PI = 3.14159;                  // implicitly public static final
    double area();                        // implicitly public abstract
    double perimeter();                   // implicitly public abstract
}
```

### 2.3.3 Default Methods (Java 8+)

Default methods provide a **concrete implementation** inside an interface. They were introduced to enable **interface evolution** — adding new methods to an interface without breaking existing implementations (the famous *Interface Evolution Problem*).

```java
public interface Vehicle {
    void start();
    default void honk() {                  // default method
        System.out.println("Beep!");
    }
}
class Car implements Vehicle {
    public void start() { System.out.println("Car starts"); }
    // honk() inherited automatically
}
```

### 2.3.4 Static Methods in Interfaces (Java 8+)

```java
public interface MathOperations {
    static int add(int a, int b) {        // static method
        return a + b;
    }
}
// Call: MathOperations.add(5, 3);
```

### 2.3.5 Multiple Inheritance of Type

A class in Java can implement **multiple interfaces** (Java's solution to the multiple inheritance problem). The class must override all abstract methods from all parent interfaces.

```java
class SmartPhone implements Phone, Camera, GPS {
    // must override all abstract methods from all 3 interfaces
}
```

Interfaces themselves can **extend multiple interfaces**:
```java
interface AdvancedPhone extends Phone, Camera { }
```

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU High-Yield:** Interfaces use the keyword **`extends`** when one interface inherits another (not `implements`).

### 2.3.6 The Diamond Problem and Resolution

When a class inherits two default methods with the **same signature** from two interfaces, it must **explicitly override** the conflicting method:

```java
interface A { default void show() { System.out.println("A"); } }
interface B { default void show() { System.out.println("B"); } }
class C implements A, B {
    @Override
    public void show() {                  // MUST override
        A.super.show();                   // call A's version
    }
}
```

### 2.3.7 Interface vs Abstract Class — KTU Comparison Table

| Feature | Interface | Abstract Class |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword | `interface` | `abstract class` |
| Method types | Abstract, default, static | Abstract + concrete |
| Variables | `public static final` only | Any type |
| Inheritance | A class can implement **many** | A class can extend **only one** |
| Constructor | ❌ Cannot have | ✅ Can have |
| Access modifiers for methods | `public` only (pre-Java 9) | Any |
| When to use | "is-a" capability / contract | "is-a" shared base with state |
