## 3.1 Walkthrough 1: `final` Method Overriding Failure

**Question:** Analyze the following code. What happens at compile time and why?

```java
class Bank {
    final double getRateOfInterest() {
        return 5.5;
    }
}
class SBIBank extends Bank {
    double getRateOfInterest() {   // line A
        return 6.5;
    }
}
class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SBIBank s = new SBIBank();
        System.out.println(s.getRateOfInterest());
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Logical Analysis

| Step | Compiler / JVM Action | Result |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `javac Bank.java` is invoked | `Bank.class` generated |
| 2 | `javac SBIBank.java` invoked | Compiler sees `SBIBank extends Bank` |
| 3 | Compiler checks `getRateOfInterest()` in `SBIBank` | Tries to override parent's method |
| 4 | Compiler reads parent's method signature | Sees `final` keyword |
| 5 | **Compile-time error emitted** at line A | `error: getRateOfInterest() in SBIBank cannot override getRateOfInterest() in Bank; overridden method is final` |
| 6 | `javac Test.java` invoked | Compilation **fails** because `SBIBank.class` was not produced |

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Valuation Pitfall:** Many students write "compilation error" but forget to **state the exact error message**. Examiners award partial marks for the cause. Always say: *"`final` methods cannot be overridden."*

---

## 3.2 Walkthrough 2: `final` Class Cannot Be Inherited

```java
final class ImmutableString {
    private final char[] value;
    ImmutableString(char[] v) { this.value = v.clone(); }
    public char charAt(int i) { return value[i]; }
}

// Attempting inheritance:
class MutableString extends ImmutableString {   // line B
    // ...
}
```

**Step-by-Step Reasoning:**

1. Class `ImmutableString` is declared **`final`**.
2. The Java Language Specification (JLS §8.1.1.2) states: *"It is a compile-time error if the class is declared `final` and another class attempts to extend it."*
3. At `line B`, the compiler detects `extends ImmutableString`.
4. **Compile-time error**: `cannot inherit from final ImmutableString`.
5. The entire project fails to compile.

> [!NOTE]
> **Engineering Use Case:** The `String` class, all wrapper classes (`Integer`, `Double`, `Boolean`), and `java.lang.Math` are all declared `final` by JDK designers. This guarantees their behaviour cannot be corrupted by inheritance.

