## 3.3 Walkthrough 3: Creating and Using a Package

**Task:** Create a package `com.ktu.geometry` containing a `Circle` class, then use it from a different class.

### Step 1: Folder Structure
```
project/
└── src/
    └── com/ktu/geometry/
        └── Circle.java
    └── com/ktu/app/
        └── MainApp.java
```

### Step 2: The Circle class (in package `com.ktu.geometry`)

```java
package com.ktu.geometry;

public class Circle {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(double radius) {
        if (radius < 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Negative radius");
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    public double getRadius() { return radius; }

    public double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }

    public double circumference() {
        return 2 * Math.PI * radius;
    }
}
```

### Step 3: A helper class in the same package

```java
package com.ktu.geometry;

public class CircleUtils {
    public static double compareAreas(Circle a, Circle b) {
        return a.area() - b.area();
    }
}
```

### Step 4: The Main class (in a different package `com.ktu.app`)

```java
package com.ktu.app;

import com.ktu.geometry.Circle;
// import com.ktu.geometry.*;   // alternative: wildcard

public class MainApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Circle c1 = new Circle(5.0);
        Circle c2 = new Circle(7.0);

        System.out.println("c1 area = " + c1.area());
        System.out.println("c2 area = " + c2.area());
        // CircleUtils.compareAreas(c1, c2);   // need to import CircleUtils too
    }
}
```

### Step 5: Compilation and Execution

```bash
cd project/src
javac com/ktu/geometry/*.java
javac -cp . com/ktu/app/MainApp.java
java -cp . com.ktu.app.MainApp
```

**Expected Output:**
```
c1 area = 78.53981633974483
c2 area = 153.93804002589985
```

### Reasoning Chain

| Step | Action | Result |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `Circle` declared in package `com.ktu.geometry` | Maps to folder `com/ktu/geometry/` |
| 2 | `MainApp` declared in package `com.ktu.app` | Maps to folder `com/ktu/app/` |
| 3 | `import com.ktu.geometry.Circle;` | Compiler resolves the class location |
| 4 | Compiler walks **CLASSPATH** (here `.`) | Finds `com/ktu/geometry/Circle.class` |
| 5 | Linking successful | `MainApp.class` is generated |
| 6 | JVM loads `MainApp` | Sees reference to `Circle` |
| 7 | JVM loads `Circle` from CLASSPATH | Success |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Frequent Question:** *Why do we need both a folder structure AND the `package` declaration?*
> **Answer:** The `package` declaration is a **logical name** for the compiler/JVM. The **folder structure** is the **physical mapping**. Both must match; otherwise the class loader fails with `ClassNotFoundException`.

