## 3.4 Walkthrough 4: Interface Implementation and Multiple Inheritance

```java
interface Drawable {
    void draw();                              // abstract
    default void showInfo() {                 // default
        System.out.println("Drawable object");
    }
}

interface Movable {
    void move(int x, int y);                  // abstract
}

interface Resizable {
    void resize(double factor);               // abstract
    default void showInfo() {                 // default - same signature as Drawable!
        System.out.println("Resizable object");
    }
}

// Multiple interface implementation
class Sprite implements Drawable, Movable, Resizable {
    private int x, y;
    private double size;

    public Sprite(int x, int y, double size) {
        this.x = x; this.y = y; this.size = size;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing sprite at (" + x + "," + y + ")");
    }

    @Override
    public void move(int x, int y) {
        this.x = x; this.y = y;
        System.out.println("Moved to (" + x + "," + y + ")");
    }

    @Override
    public void resize(double factor) {
        this.size *= factor;
        System.out.println("New size = " + size);
    }

    @Override
    public void showInfo() {                  // MUST override - diamond problem
        Drawable.super.showInfo();            // explicitly choose Drawable's version
    }
}

public class InterfaceDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Sprite s = new Sprite(0, 0, 10.0);
        s.draw();
        s.move(5, 5);
        s.resize(2.0);
        s.showInfo();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Drawing sprite at (0,0)
Moved to (5,5)
New size = 20.0
Drawable object
```

### Step-by-Step Trace

| Step | Action | Reasoning |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `Sprite` implements three interfaces | It inherits **3 abstract methods** + 2 default methods |
| 2 | `draw()`, `move()`, `resize()` implemented | All 3 abstract methods satisfied |
| 3 | Two default `showInfo()` inherited from `Drawable` and `Resizable` | **Diamond problem** — ambiguous |
| 4 | Compiler **forces** `Sprite` to override `showInfo()` | Resolution rule: implementing class must disambiguate |
| 5 | Inside `showInfo()`, `Drawable.super.showInfo();` chosen | Java 8+ syntax: `InterfaceName.super.method()` |
| 6 | `s.showInfo()` is called at runtime | JVM dispatches to `Sprite.showInfo()`, which delegates to `Drawable`'s default |

> [!NOTE]
> **Engineering Significance:** Default methods are how Java's own Collections API evolved. `Iterable.forEach()` (added in Java 8) is a default method — millions of existing `Iterable` implementations did not need to be modified.

