## 3.5 Walkthrough 5: `final` Variable Usage Patterns

```java
public class FinalVariableDemo {
    // (a) Static final — class constant
    public static final String COMPANY_NAME = "KTU Kerala";

    // (b) Instance final — blank, initialized in constructor
    private final int rollNumber;

    // (c) Final reference — object content may change, but reference cannot
    private final StringBuilder nameBuilder = new StringBuilder("Roll: ");

    public FinalVariableDemo(int roll) {
        this.rollNumber = roll;     // blank final initialized here
        this.nameBuilder.append(roll);
    }

    public void demonstrate() {
        // rollNumber = 100;          // ERROR - blank final can only be assigned in constructor
        nameBuilder.append(" - Verified");   // OK - mutating object's state
        // nameBuilder = new StringBuilder();  // ERROR - reference cannot change

        System.out.println(COMPANY_NAME);
        System.out.println(rollNumber);
        System.out.println(nameBuilder.toString());
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new FinalVariableDemo(415).demonstrate();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
KTU Kerala
415
Roll: 415 - Verified
```

**Key Insights:**

1. `final` on a *reference* does **not** make the object immutable — it only prevents the reference from being reassigned.
2. The `StringBuilder`'s state is still mutable.
3. A `final` variable can be initialized only **once** in its lifetime.
