### Question B: Interfaces and Multiple Inheritance

**[KTU University Exam – June 2024 Pattern]**

**(a)** What is an interface in Java? Explain how interfaces support multiple inheritance of type. Provide a code example demonstrating a class implementing multiple interfaces. *(7 marks)*

**(b)** Explain default methods and static methods in interfaces introduced in Java 8. With a suitable example, illustrate how the *diamond problem* is resolved in interfaces. *(7 marks)*

---

#### Model Solution for (a):

**Definition of Interface**

An *interface* in Java is a reference type, similar to a class, used to specify a *contract* that implementing classes must fulfil. From Java 8 onwards, an interface may contain:
- **Abstract methods** (implicitly `public abstract`)
- **Default methods** (with implementation, marked `default`)
- **Static methods** (with implementation, marked `static`)
- **Constants** (implicitly `public static final`)
- **Nested types** (implicitly `public static`)

**Interface declaration syntax:**

```java
access_modifier interface InterfaceName [extends OtherInterface1, OtherInterface2] {
    // constants
    // abstract methods
    // default methods
    // static methods
}
```

**Multiple Inheritance of Type**

Java does not support multiple inheritance of *classes* (to avoid the diamond problem of state), but it does support **multiple inheritance of *type*** through interfaces. A class can implement one or more interfaces, inheriting all their abstract method signatures. The class must override all inherited abstract methods or declare itself as `abstract`.

**Code Example:**

```java
// First interface
interface Printer {
    void print(String document);
    default void showStatus() {
        System.out.println("Printer ready");
    }
}

// Second interface
interface Scanner {
    void scan(String document);
}

// Third interface combining the two
interface MultiFunctionDevice extends Printer, Scanner {
    void fax(String document);
}

// Class implementing multiple interfaces
class OfficeMachine implements MultiFunctionDevice {
    private String model;

    public OfficeMachine(String model) {
        this.model = model;
    }

    @Override
    public void print(String document) {
        System.out.println(model + " printing: " + document);
    }

    @Override
    public void scan(String document) {
        System.out.println(model + " scanning: " + document);
    }

    @Override
    public void fax(String document) {
        System.out.println(model + " faxing: " + document);
    }
}

public class InterfaceMultiDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        OfficeMachine om = new OfficeMachine("HP-LJ4250");
        om.print("Annual Report");
        om.scan("Invoice");
        om.fax("Contract");
        om.showStatus();        // inherited default from Printer
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
HP-LJ4250 printing: Annual Report
HP-LJ4250 scanning: Invoice
HP-LJ4250 faxing: Contract
Printer ready
```

**Analysis:**
- `OfficeMachine` inherits abstract methods from `Printer`, `Scanner`, and `MultiFunctionDevice` (which extends the first two).
- It must override all four abstract methods (`print`, `scan`, `fax`, and `MultiFunctionDevice`'s own abstract members).
- The default `showStatus()` is inherited automatically without override.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning:** A frequent mistake is writing `class OfficeMachine extends MultiFunctionDevice`. **Interfaces use `implements`, not `extends`** (only when a class *implements* an interface). Conversely, when one interface inherits another, it uses **`extends`**. Examiners deduct 1–2 marks for this confusion.

---

#### Model Solution for (b):

**Default Methods in Interfaces (Java 8+)**

A *default method* is a concrete method declared inside an interface using the `default` keyword. It allows developers to add new methods to existing interfaces **without breaking binary compatibility** with code written for older versions.

```java
interface Vehicle {
    void start();
    default void stop() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle stopped");
    }
}
```

**Why default methods?**
Before Java 8, adding a new method to an interface (such as `forEach()` in `Iterable`) would break **all** existing implementations because they would suddenly be missing that abstract method. Default methods solve this by providing a fallback implementation.

**Static Methods in Interfaces (Java 8+)**

Static methods in interfaces are utility methods belonging to the interface itself (not to implementing classes). They are called using the interface name.

```java
interface Calculator {
    static int square(int n) {
        return n * n;
    }
}
// Call: Calculator.square(5);   // returns 25
```

**The Diamond Problem in Interfaces**

The *diamond problem* arises when a class inherits two default methods with the **same signature** from two different interfaces. Since Java cannot decide which implementation to use, the implementing class **must explicitly override** the conflicting method.

**Example demonstrating the resolution:**

```java
interface Engine {
    default void start() {
        System.out.println("Engine started");
    }
}

interface Electric {
    default void start() {
        System.out.println("Electric motor engaged");
    }
}

// Hybrid car inherits conflicting start() from both interfaces
class HybridCar implements Engine, Electric {
    private String model;

    public HybridCar(String model) {
        this.model = model;
    }

    // MUST override to resolve diamond problem
    @Override
    public void start() {
        System.out.println(model + " hybrid start sequence:");
        Engine.super.start();        // delegate to Engine
        Electric.super.start();      // delegate to Electric
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        HybridCar hc = new HybridCar("Toyota Prius");
        hc.start();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Toyota Prius hybrid start sequence:
Engine started
Electric motor engaged
```

**Resolution Mechanism:**

| Step | Action | Rule |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `HybridCar` inherits `start()` from both `Engine` and `Electric` | **Conflict detected** by compiler |
| 2 | Compiler forces `HybridCar` to override `start()` | **Rule 1:** Class method wins over default |
| 3 | Inside override, `Engine.super.start()` and `Electric.super.start()` called explicitly | **Java 8+ syntax:** `InterfaceName.super.methodName()` |
| 4 | Both inherited implementations are executed in order | Programmer controls the order |

**Rules of Default Method Resolution (in priority order):**
1. Methods declared in the class (or its superclass) win over default methods.
2. Sub-interface methods win over super-interface default methods.
3. If still ambiguous, the implementing class **must** override the method explicitly.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning:** Students often write `super.start();` inside the override. This is **wrong** — `super` refers to the *class* hierarchy, not the *interface*. The correct syntax is `Engine.super.start();`. Examiners deduct marks for this error.

