```

**Reading the diagram:**
- The **left branch (Error)** represents fatal, system-level issues that applications should not catch.
- The **right branch (Exception)** is further split: its **direct subclasses are checked**, while the **RuntimeException subtree is unchecked**.

### 4.2 Checked Exception Flow Control (Mermaid Block Diagram)

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Caller Method] --> B[Callee Method declares: throws IOException]
    B --> C{try block executes}
    C -->|No exception| D[Continue normally]
    C -->|Checked exception thrown| E{Matching catch block exists?}
    E -->|Yes| F[catch block executes]
    E -->|No| G[Exception propagates up the call stack]
    F --> H[finally block executes]
    D --> H
    G --> I[Search for catch in caller method]
    I --> E
    H --> J[Method returns control to caller]
```

### 4.3 Catch-or-Specify Decision Flow (Mermaid)

```mermaid
graph TD
    START[Code may throw checked exception] --> Q1{Is it inside a try-catch block?}
    Q1 -->|Yes| HANDLED[Exception is HANDLED locally]
    Q1 -->|No| Q2{Does the method declare it in throws clause?}
    Q2 -->|Yes| DECLARED[Exception is DECLARED to caller]
    Q2 -->|No| ERROR[COMPILE-TIME ERROR: Unhandled exception]
    HANDLED --> SUCCESS[Compilation succeeds]
    DECLARED --> SUCCESS
    ERROR --> FAIL[Compilation fails]
```

This decision flow is the **mental model** you should carry into your KTU exams when asked "What happens if a checked exception is not handled?"
