> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout — Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Confusing `throw` and `throws`:** Remember: `throw` (verb — actively throws an object) vs. `throws` (noun-like — declares the type in signature). This is a **favourite trick question** in KTU exams.
> 2. **Forgetting to declare `throws`:** Any method that calls `FileReader`, `BufferedReader.readLine()`, `Thread.sleep()`, etc., MUST handle or declare the checked exception. Code without it **will not compile**.
> 3. **Wrong catch-block order:** Catching `Exception` BEFORE `IOException` causes an "unreachable code" compile error. Always catch the **most specific** exception first.
> 4. **Ignoring the `finally` block:** Examiners specifically test whether `finally` runs even when `catch` re-throws the exception.
> 5. **Treating `RuntimeException` as checked:** `NullPointerException` and `ArithmeticException` are **unchecked**, even though they are subclasses of `Exception`. A common KTU trap.

