### Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- ✅ **Checked exceptions** are verified at **compile-time** by the Java compiler.
- ✅ They are subclasses of `java.lang.Exception` but **NOT** of `java.lang.RuntimeException`.
- ✅ The **Catch-or-Specify Rule** is mandatory: handle via `try-catch` **or** declare via `throws`.
- ✅ `throw` (lowercase, inside body) is for **triggering** an exception; `throws` (in signature) is for **declaring** it.
- ✅ Multiple checked exceptions can be declared using commas: `throws IOException, SQLException`.
- ✅ `catch` blocks must be ordered from **most specific to most general** subclass.
- ✅ The `finally` block **always executes**, even if `catch` re-throws or `try` returns normally.
- ✅ **Try-with-resources** (Java 7+) auto-closes resources and is the **modern best practice** for I/O.
- ✅ Common checked exceptions: `IOException`, `FileNotFoundException`, `SQLException`, `ClassNotFoundException`, `InterruptedException`, `ParseException`.
- ✅ Custom checked exceptions are created by extending `java.lang.Exception`.
- ✅ **Errors** (e.g., `OutOfMemoryError`) are NOT exceptions and should not be caught in application code.
- ✅ A method that overrides a parent method **cannot throw more checked exceptions** than the parent (Liskov-friendly rule).
- ✅ Remember to **close resources** in `finally` or use try-with-resources to avoid resource leaks.
