## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In the Java programming language, **Multiple Catch Clauses** refer to a structured exception-handling construct where a single `try` block is followed by two or more `catch` blocks, each parameterized with a distinct exception class. The Java Virtual Machine (JVM) evaluates these clauses sequentially (top-down) upon the detection of an exception, invoking the **first matching handler** whose declared exception type is compatible (via class hierarchy or interface implementation) with the dynamically dispatched thrown object.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight (Module 3 - Exception Handling):**
> Students are expected to comprehend, trace, and implement multiple catch handlers, understand the **order-of-specificity rule**, and utilize the **multi-catch operator (`|`)** introduced in Java SE 7 (JSR 334 - Project Coin).

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine a **hospital emergency triage system**:

- A patient (the *thrown exception object*) arrives at the emergency desk (the `try` block).
- The triage nurse has a list of specialists (`catch` blocks) — a cardiologist, a neurologist, a general physician, and a catch-all trauma surgeon.
- The patient is routed to the **first specialist whose expertise matches the condition**. Once treated, the patient does not visit any other specialist.
- **Critical rule**: The cardiologist (specific) must be listed *before* the general physician (generic). Otherwise, the general physician would "steal" all heart-attack cases, leaving the cardiologist idle — a *compile-time error* in Java called **"unreachable catch block"**.

### 1.3 Core Terminology

| Term | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `try` | The guarded region where an exception may be raised |
| `catch` | The exception-handling subroutine |
| `Throwable` | The root superclass of all errors and exceptions in Java |
| `Exception` | Subclass of `Throwable` representing recoverable conditions |
| **Unreachable Code** | A `catch` block that the compiler knows can never execute |
| **Multi-catch** | A single `catch` clause handling multiple exception types separated by `\|` |
| **Polymorphic Dispatch** | JVM mechanism selecting the correct catch based on runtime type |

> [!NOTE]
> The keyword **`finally`** may be optionally appended after the last `catch` block, ensuring execution of cleanup code regardless of whether an exception was thrown, caught, or propagated.
>
