## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Worked Example 1 — Basic Multiple Catch (Order-Specific)

**Problem Trace:** Determine the output of the following program and explain each transition.

```java
public class MultipleCatchDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            int[] arr = {10, 20, 30};
            int result = arr[5] / arr[1];   // Line A
            System.out.println("Result: " + result);
        }
        catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Arithmetic error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
            System.out.println("Array index error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Generic error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        finally {
            System.out.println("Cleanup complete.");
        }
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Trace:**

| Step | Line | Action | State |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `int[] arr = {10, 20, 30};` | Array initialized on heap. | Normal flow |
| 2 | `arr[5]` | Evaluates to `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` (index 5 invalid for length 3). | **Exception thrown** before division |
| 3 | JVM dispatch | Searches catch list top-down. | First match: `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` |
| 4 | `catch (ArithmeticException)` | **Skipped** — type mismatch. | Unmatched |
| 5 | `catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException)` | **Executed.** Prints message. | Matched |
| 6 | Subsequent catches | **Skipped.** | Bypassed |
| 7 | `finally` | Always executes. | Prints "Cleanup complete." |

**Final Output:**
```
Array index error: Index 5 out of bounds for length 3
Cleanup complete.
```

> [!NOTE]
> The `ArithmeticException` handler is *not* triggered, even though division appears in the expression, because short-circuit evaluation throws the `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` first (left-to-right operand evaluation).

---

### 3.2 Worked Example 2 — Multi-Catch Syntax (Java 7+)

**Demonstrating the unified handler pattern:**

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.sql.*;

public class MultiCatchExample {
    public void performIO() throws IOException, SQLException {
        // Simulated I/O and database operations
        if (Math.random() > 0.5)
            throw new IOException("File not found");
        else
            throw new SQLException("DB connection lost");
    }

    public void execute() {
        try {
            performIO();
        }
        catch (IOException | SQLException e) {    // Multi-catch
            System.err.println("Recoverable error: " + e.getMessage());
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new MultiCatchExample().execute();
    }
}
```

**Analysis Matrix:**

| Feature | Traditional Multiple Catch | Multi-Catch |
|---|---|---|
| Lines of code | `catch (IOException e) { ... } catch (SQLException e) { ... }` | `catch (IOException \| SQLException e) { ... }` |
| Bytecode behavior | Two separate exception tables entries | Single exception table entry with multiple ranges |
| Re-throw enhancement | Cannot re-throw as either type | Java 7+ allows `final` re-throw inference |
| `e` modifier | Modifiable | Implicitly `final` |

