## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023 Model]**
*What is a multiple catch clause in Java? Why is the order of catch blocks important?*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

A multiple catch clause is an exception-handling construct in Java where a single `try` block is followed by two or more `catch` blocks, each designed to handle a specific type of exception. **(1 mark)**

When an exception is thrown, the JVM inspects the catch blocks in sequential order and executes the **first** block whose parameter type is compatible with the thrown exception. **(1 mark)**

The order is important because more specific (subclass) exceptions must be caught **before** their superclass types. If a superclass catch precedes a subclass catch, the subclass handler becomes unreachable, resulting in a **compile-time error**. For example, `catch (Exception e)` must come *after* `catch (ArithmeticException e)`. **(1 mark)**

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam – June 2024 Model]**
*Explain the multi-catch feature introduced in Java 7 with a suitable example.*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

Java 7 introduced the **multi-catch** feature, which allows a single `catch` block to handle multiple unrelated exception types using the `|` (bitwise OR) operator. **(1 mark)**

**Syntax:**
```java
try {
    // risky code
}
catch (IOException | SQLException e) {
    System.err.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
}
```

The parameter `e` is implicitly `final`, meaning it cannot be reassigned within the catch block. **(1 mark)**

**Advantage:** It reduces code duplication when multiple exception types require identical recovery logic, improving readability and maintainability. **(1 mark)**

---

### 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Module Internal Choice)

---

### **Question A (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2022 Model]`

**(a)** Explain the concept of multiple catch clauses in Java with a suitable example program. Discuss the rule of ordering catch blocks. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program that demonstrates both **traditional multiple catch** and **multi-catch (Java 7+)** syntax. Explain the differences between them. **(7 marks)**

---

#### **Model Solution for Q.A(a):**

**Definition (2 marks):**
Multiple catch clauses allow a `try` block to be followed by multiple `catch` blocks, each handling a different exception type. When an exception occurs, the JVM identifies the matching catch handler based on the runtime type of the exception object and the declared parameter type of each catch.

**Example Program (3 marks):**

```java
public class ExceptionOrder {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            int a = Integer.parseInt(args[0]);
            int b = Integer.parseInt(args[1]);
            int c = a / b;
            System.out.println("Result = " + c);
        }
        catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero.");
        }
        catch (NumberFormatException e) {
            System.out.println("Invalid numeric input.");
        }
        catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
            System.out.println("Please provide two arguments.");
        }
        catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Unexpected error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Ordering Rule (2 marks):**
Catch blocks must be ordered from **most specific (subclass)** to **most general (superclass)**. The JVM uses an "is-a" inheritance check, so a `catch (Exception e)` would also match all subclass exceptions. Placing it first would make subsequent subclass handlers **unreachable**, causing a compile error.

---

#### **Model Solution for Q.A(b):**

**Traditional Multiple Catch (3 marks):**

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.sql.*;

public class TraditionalCatch {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt");
            Connection con = null; // simulated
            // perform risky operations
        }
        catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
            System.out.println("File missing: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("I/O failure: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        catch (SQLException e) {
            System.out.println("DB error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Multi-Catch Syntax (2 marks):**

```java
catch (FileNotFoundException | IOException | SQLException e) {
    System.out.println("Resource error: " + e.getMessage());
}
```

**Differences Table (2 marks):**

| Aspect | Traditional | Multi-Catch |
|---|---|---|
| Code Volume | Verbose, duplicated handler | Concise, single handler |
| Handler Logic | Can be different per type | Must be identical for all listed types |
| Parameter `e` | Modifiable | Implicitly `final` |
| Alternative types allowed | Only unrelated types via `\|` | Same `\|` syntax |

