# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition

> [!NOTE]
> **Thread Creation in Java** is the process of instantiating a separate, lightweight, independent path of execution within a running program (JVM process) so that multiple tasks can run concurrently, leveraging the CPU's multi-core architecture.

In the context of the **KTU 2024 Scheme (PEMRT415 - Object Oriented Programming)**, *Creating a Thread* refers specifically to the Java mechanisms provided by the `java.lang` package to define the entry point (`run()` method) of a new thread of control and then invoking the JVM thread scheduler to begin its execution via the `start()` method.

The Java API offers **two principal ways** to create a thread:

1. **By extending the `java.lang.Thread` class** (Inheritance-based approach).
2. **By implementing the `java.lang.Runnable` interface** (Interface-based approach).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight (Module 3 – Multithreading):** Students must be able to differentiate between the two creation methods, justify the choice of one over the other, and write the exact syntax for `Thread` constructors, `start()`, `run()`, `sleep()`, `join()`, and `isAlive()`.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine a **busy railway reservation counter** that has only **one clerk (single-threaded program)**. Customers stand in a long queue. To serve faster, the railway opens **three more counters (multiple threads)**. Each counter is essentially a *thread* — they share the same railway station building (process memory & resources), but each clerk follows their **own predefined procedure (the `run()` method)** on how to issue a ticket.

Now, *creating* a thread is like:
- **Training a new clerk** (defining *what* the thread will do — the `run()` method), and
- **Placing them at a counter and saying "Start serving"** (calling the `start()` method, which hands control to the OS thread scheduler).

> A thread is *not* a process. Threads share the **same heap memory** but have **independent stacks** and **program counters**. This is what makes multithreading faster than spawning multiple processes.

## 1.3 Key Terminology

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **Process** | An independent executing program with its own memory space. |
| **Thread** | A lightweight subunit of a process; shares memory with sibling threads. |
| **Main Thread** | The thread that begins execution when a Java program starts (`main()` method). |
| **Time Slicing** | The CPU scheduler allocating small time units to each thread. |
| **Concurrency** | Multiple threads making progress in overlapping time periods. |
| **Parallelism** | Multiple threads executing *simultaneously* on different CPU cores. |

