# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Method 1 — Extending the `Thread` Class

In this approach, the user class **inherits** from `java.lang.Thread` and **overrides** the `run()` method (which is the heart of the thread — the code that the new thread will execute).

### Step-by-Step Logic

1. Declare a subclass of `Thread`.
2. Override the `public void run()` method. Put your task code inside.
3. Instantiate the subclass → this creates a *Thread object* (not yet running).
4. Call `start()` on the object → the JVM spawns a *new call stack*, schedules the thread, and invokes `run()` asynchronously.
5. The original (caller) thread continues immediately after `start()` returns.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Calling `run()` **directly** does **NOT** create a new thread. It executes like a normal method in the *caller's* thread. Only `start()` spawns a new thread of execution.

## 2.2 Method 2 — Implementing the `Runnable` Interface

The `Runnable` interface is a **Functional Interface** (SAM — Single Abstract Method) that declares a single method:

```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Runnable {
    void run();
}
```

### Step-by-Step Logic

1. Implement `Runnable` in your class and provide the `run()` implementation.
2. Create a `Thread` object, passing your `Runnable` instance to its constructor.
3. Call `start()` on the `Thread` object.

### Standard `Thread` Constructors

| Constructor | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `Thread()` | Creates a thread with a default name (Thread-0, Thread-1, …). |
| `Thread(Runnable target)` | Wraps a `Runnable` object as a new thread. |
| `Thread(String name)` | Creates a thread with a custom name. |
| `Thread(Runnable target, String name)` | Wraps a `Runnable` and assigns a name. |
| `Thread(Runnable target, String name, long stackSize)` | Allows specifying stack size (advanced). |

## 2.3 Comparison: `Thread` vs `Runnable`

| Criterion | Extending `Thread` | Implementing `Runnable` |
|---|---|---|
| Inheritance | Occupies the single-inheritance slot. | Leaves room to extend any other class. |
| Object Reusability | Each thread object is *the task* itself — hard to share. | A single `Runnable` can be passed to **multiple** `Thread` objects (task reuse). |
| Coupling | Tightly couples the **task** with the **threading mechanism**. | Decouples the **task** (what to do) from the **thread** (how to execute). |
| Design Heuristic | Avoid in production. | **Preferred by Java community and KTU examiners.** |
| Supports Lambda? | No. | Yes (since Java 8 — `@FunctionalInterface`). |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Examiner Insight:** When a 14-mark question asks "Discuss two ways of creating a thread", the marking scheme typically awards **2 marks** for inheritance syntax, **2 marks** for interface syntax, **4 marks** for working code, and **3+3** for comparative analysis and the `start()` vs `run()` distinction.

## 2.4 Real-World Utility

- **GUI Applications** (Swing/JavaFX) — background tasks without freezing the UI.
- **Web Servers** (Tomcat) — each request handled by a worker thread.
- **Real-time Systems** — sensor data acquisition threads, logging threads, control threads.
- **Game Development** — render thread, physics thread, input thread.

