# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

This section presents the **complete, exam-ready code templates** for both thread-creation methods, along with a worked-output trace commonly asked in KTU papers.

## 3.1 Method 1 — Extending `Thread` (Complete Code Template)

```java
// File: MyThreadExt.java
class MyThreadExt extends Thread {
    private String threadName;

    // Constructor
    public MyThreadExt(String name) {
        this.threadName = name;
        System.out.println("Constructing thread: " + threadName);
    }

    // The actual task — overrides Thread's empty run() method
    @Override
    public void run() {
        try {
            for (int i = 5; i > 0; i--) {
                System.out.println("Thread " + threadName + " : " + i);
                Thread.sleep(1000);  // pause for 1 second
            }
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            System.out.println(threadName + " interrupted.");
        }
        System.out.println("Thread " + threadName + " exiting.");
    }
}

// Driver class
public class ThreadExtDemo {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        MyThreadExt t1 = new MyThreadExt("Thread-1");
        MyThreadExt t2 = new MyThreadExt("Thread-2");

        t1.start();   // <-- starts a new call stack
        t2.start();   // <-- starts a new call stack

        // main thread waits for both to finish
        try {
            t1.join();
            t2.join();
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            System.out.println("Main thread interrupted.");
        }
        System.out.println("Main thread exiting.");
    }
}
```

### Expected Output (order of lines from t1 and t2 may interleave)

```text
Constructing thread: Thread-1
Constructing thread: Thread-2
Thread Thread-1 : 5
Thread Thread-2 : 5
Thread Thread-1 : 4
Thread Thread-2 : 4
Thread Thread-1 : 3
Thread Thread-2 : 3
Thread Thread-1 : 2
Thread Thread-2 : 2
Thread Thread-1 : 1
Thread Thread-2 : 1
Thread Thread-1 exiting.
Thread Thread-2 exiting.
Main thread exiting.
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The output order between the two threads is **non-deterministic** — the JVM thread scheduler decides. This unpredictability is itself a frequently asked KTU question: *"Why does the output change on each run?"*

## 3.2 Method 2 — Implementing `Runnable` (Complete Code Template)

```java
// File: MyRunnable.java
class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
    private String threadName;

    public MyRunnable(String name) {
        this.threadName = name;
        System.out.println("Creating runnable task: " + threadName);
    }

    @Override
    public void run() {
        try {
            for (int i = 5; i > 0; i--) {
                System.out.println("Runnable " + threadName + " : " + i);
                Thread.sleep(1000);
            }
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            System.out.println(threadName + " interrupted.");
        }
        System.out.println("Runnable " + threadName + " exiting.");
    }
}

// Driver class
public class RunnableDemo {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        MyRunnable r1 = new MyRunnable("Task-A");
        MyRunnable r2 = new MyRunnable("Task-B");

        Thread t1 = new Thread(r1, "Worker-1");
        Thread t2 = new Thread(r2, "Worker-2");

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
    }
}
```

## 3.3 Lambda-Shortcut for `Runnable` (Java 8+ — Bonus Marks)

Since `Runnable` is a `@FunctionalInterface`, the lambda syntax is fully valid and **often rewarded by KTU examiners** for compactness:

```java
public class LambdaThreadDemo {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        // Anonymous lambda-based thread
        Thread t = new Thread(() -> {
            for (int i = 3; i > 0; i--) {
                System.out.println("Lambda Thread: " + i);
                try { Thread.sleep(500); } catch (InterruptedException e) { }
            }
        }, "LambdaWorker");

        t.start();
    }
}
```

## 3.4 Analytical Trace Table — `start()` vs `run()`

| Action | Number of Threads in Program | Where does `run()` execute? |
|---|---|---|
| `t.run();` | **1** (only the calling thread) | Calling thread's stack. |
| `t.start();` | **2** (caller + new thread) | A new, separate call stack. |

> [!WARNING]
> This is the **#1 most-missed KTU question**. A direct `run()` call is **not** multithreading. A `start()` call is. Do not confuse them.

## 3.5 Thread Lifecycle States (Transitions)

A thread passes through the following states (mapped to `Thread.State` enum in Java):

| State | Description |
|---|---|
| **NEW** | Thread object is created but `start()` not yet called. |
| **RUNNABLE** | `start()` called; waiting for CPU time. |
| **BLOCKED** | Waiting to acquire a monitor lock (synchronized). |
| **WAITING** | `wait()`, `join()`, or `LockSupport.park()` called indefinitely. |
| **TIMED_WAITING** | `sleep(ms)`, `wait(ms)`, `join(ms)` called. |
| **TERMINATED** | `run()` returned or an uncaught exception terminated it. |

