# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

### **Q1. Differentiate between `start()` and `run()` methods of the `Thread` class. Why is `run()` not sufficient to start a new thread?**
`[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**Model Answer:**

The `start()` method is a member of the `Thread` class that performs **two critical jobs**: (i) it registers the thread with the Java thread scheduler, and (ii) it invokes the `run()` method in a **newly created call stack**, thereby beginning a *new* thread of execution.

In contrast, `run()` is simply a regular instance method. If called directly on a `Thread` object (e.g., `t.run();`), it executes **synchronously** in the *caller's* thread — no new thread is created. The program remains single-threaded for that code path.

Hence, calling `run()` directly defeats the purpose of multithreading; only `start()` causes true parallel/concurrent execution.

---

### **Q2. What is the role of the `Runnable` interface in Java? Why is it preferred over extending the `Thread` class?**
`[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Model Answer:**

`java.lang.Runnable` is a **functional interface** with a single abstract method `void run();`. Any class implementing `Runnable` must define the code that should execute when the thread runs.

It is **preferred** over extending `Thread` because:

1. Java does not support multiple inheritance. Extending `Thread` blocks the class from inheriting any other useful class; implementing `Runnable` leaves the inheritance slot free.
2. It **decouples the task (the `run()` logic) from the threading mechanism (the `Thread` object)**, yielding cleaner object-oriented design.
3. The **same `Runnable` object can be passed to multiple `Thread` instances**, allowing easy reuse of the task.
4. It is compatible with **lambda expressions** introduced in Java 8.

