### **Question B (14 Marks)**  *(Alternative Choice)*
`[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023 - Module 3 Choice 2]`

**(a)** What is a thread? Explain the lifecycle of a thread in Java with a neat diagram. **(7 marks)**
**(b)** Write a Java program that creates three threads named "A", "B", and "C". Each thread should print its name five times. Use the `Runnable` interface. **(7 marks)**

---

#### **Model Solution for (a) — Thread & Lifecycle**

A **thread** is the smallest unit of execution within a process. A Java program implicitly starts with the **main thread** (which runs `main()`). Additional threads share the same heap memory but have independent stacks and program counters.

**Thread States (in order):**

1. **NEW** — object created, `start()` not called.
2. **RUNNABLE** — `start()` invoked; thread is ready or running.
3. **BLOCKED / WAITING / TIMED_WAITING** — thread is paused.
4. **TERMINATED** — `run()` has completed.

(Refer to the Mermaid state diagram in Section 4.1 for the visual representation.)

---

#### **Model Solution for (b) — Three Named Threads Using `Runnable`**

```java
class NamedPrinter implements Runnable {
    private String name;

    public NamedPrinter(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void run() {
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.println("Thread " + name + " : count " + i);
            try {
                Thread.sleep(200);
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                System.out.println(name + " interrupted");
            }
        }
    }
}

public class ThreeThreadDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        Thread t1 = new Thread(new NamedPrinter("A"), "A");
        Thread t2 = new Thread(new NamedPrinter("B"), "B");
        Thread t3 = new Thread(new NamedPrinter("C"), "C");

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
        t3.start();

        t1.join();
        t2.join();
        t3.join();

        System.out.println("All three threads completed.");
    }
}
```

**Expected Behaviour:** All three threads execute concurrently, so the order of `Thread A`, `Thread B`, and `Thread C` lines is *interleaved* and *non-deterministic* on each run.

