## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Where KTU students lose marks in "Creating Thread" questions:**
>
> 1. **Confusing `start()` with `run()`** — always call `start()`. Calling `run()` directly does **not** create a new thread; it executes in the caller's thread. (Up to **–3 marks**.)
> 2. **Forgetting to override `run()`** — `Thread.run()` does nothing by default, so the thread "completes" immediately with no visible output. (Up to **–2 marks**.)
> 3. **Assuming a deterministic output order** — KTU paper setters may explicitly ask *"why is the output different on every run?"* Answer: **thread scheduling is OS-dependent and non-deterministic**.
> 4. **Missing `throws InterruptedException` or `try-catch` around `sleep()` / `join()`** — these are *checked* exceptions. (Up to **–2 marks** for compile-error question)
> 5. **Calling `start()` twice on the same `Thread` object** — this throws `IllegalThreadStateException`. Note this carefully.
> 6. **Inheritance loss** — forgetting to mention that extending `Thread` blocks further inheritance. Often asked as a *"compare and contrast"* sub-question.

---

## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- A **thread** is a lightweight subprocess — the smallest unit of execution. **Multiple threads share heap memory but have private stacks.**
- Java provides **two ways to create a thread**: extending `Thread` and implementing `Runnable`. **Implementing `Runnable` is the preferred OOP design.**
- The `run()` method contains the **task code**; the `start()` method actually **spawns a new call stack** and schedules the thread.
- Calling `run()` directly = **no new thread**. Calling `start()` = **new thread created**.
- A new thread moves through: **NEW → RUNNABLE → (BLOCKED / WAITING / TIMED_WAITING) → TERMINATED**.
- The `Runnable` interface is a **`@FunctionalInterface`** with a single `void run()` method, supporting **lambda expressions** (Java 8+).
- Common `Thread` constructors: `Thread()`, `Thread(Runnable)`, `Thread(String)`, `Thread(Runnable, String)`.
- Output order of concurrent threads is **non-deterministic** because the **JVM thread scheduler** (OS-dependent) decides interleaving.
- Common thread methods: `start()`, `run()`, `sleep(ms)`, `join()`, `isAlive()`, `getName()`, `setName()`, `currentThread()`.
- Calling `start()` **twice** on the same `Thread` object throws **`IllegalThreadStateException`**.
- Java does **not support multiple inheritance**, so implementing `Runnable` is more flexible than extending `Thread`.

