# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

In the context of **Java Multithreading** under the KTU 2024 Scheme Object Oriented Programming (PEMRT415) syllabus, **"Suspending"** refers to the process of **temporarily halting the execution of a currently running thread** without terminating it, with the explicit capability of being **resumed later** from the exact point where it was suspended.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Definition:**
> *Suspending a thread is the act of putting an active thread into a blocked/waiting state using mechanisms like the deprecated `suspend()` method, or modern equivalents such as `wait()`, `sleep()`, or thread state transitions to `WAITING`/`TIMED_WAITING`.*

### The Three Classical Thread Control Methods (Legacy)

| Method | Purpose | Status |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `suspend()` | Stops a thread from executing | **Deprecated** (since JDK 1.2) |
| `resume()` | Resumes a suspended thread | **Deprecated** (since JDK 1.2) |
| `stop()` | Terminates a thread immediately | **Deprecated** (since JDK 1.2) |

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy — The "Pause Button" Analogy:**
> Imagine you are **watching a movie on your laptop**. The movie is like a **thread** executing a long task.
> - **Suspending** = Pressing the **⏸ PAUSE button**. The movie stops exactly where it is. You can walk away, make popcorn, and come back later.
> - **Resuming** = Pressing the **▶ PLAY button**. The movie continues from the exact frame where you paused it — it does NOT restart from the beginning.
> - **Stopping** = Closing the **laptop lid forever**. The movie ends; you cannot resume it.
> - **Why deprecated?** Imagine if pressing PAUSE could corrupt the movie file because the video decoder was halfway through reading a frame — that is exactly what `suspend()` could do to shared data structures (monitor locks) in Java.

This is precisely why KTU 2024 emphasises understanding **both** the legacy mechanism (for exam questions on deprecated APIs) **and** the modern best practice using `wait()` / `notify()` / `Lock` conditions.

## 1.3 Thread Lifecycle with Suspension States

A Java thread exists in one of **six states** (defined in `java.lang.Thread.State`):

- **NEW** — Thread object created but not yet started.
- **RUNNABLE** — Thread is executing or ready to execute.
- **BLOCKED** — Waiting to acquire a monitor lock.
- **WAITING** — Indefinitely waiting (`wait()`, `join()` without timeout, `park()`).
- **TIMED_WAITING** — Waiting with a timeout (`sleep(ms)`, `wait(ms)`, `join(ms)`).
- **TERMINATED** — Execution completed.

> [!TIP]
> When you **suspend** a thread, the JVM transitions it to the **WAITING** or **TIMED_WAITING** state, depending on whether a timeout is supplied.

