# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Exhaustive Walkthrough: The Deprecated `suspend()` Pattern

Let us analyse the canonical textbook example (commonly tested in KTU boards) to demonstrate **why** `suspend()` is dangerous.

### Source Code (Educational — Do NOT use in production)

```java
class SharedResource {
    synchronized void criticalSection() {
        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + " acquired lock");
        try { Thread.sleep(1000); } catch(Exception e) {}
        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + " releasing lock");
    }
}

class SuspendThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        Thread.currentThread().setName("Worker-1");
        SharedResource obj = new SharedResource();
        obj.criticalSection();
        // Imagine long work continues here
    }
}
```

**Analytical Steps:**

- **Step 1:** `Worker-1` enters `criticalSection()` and acquires the intrinsic monitor lock of the `SharedResource` object.
- **Step 2:** During the `Thread.sleep(1000)`, another thread calls `worker1.suspend()`.
- **Step 3:** `Worker-1` is now **frozen mid-execution**, but it **still owns the monitor lock**.
- **Step 4:** Any other thread attempting to call `obj.criticalSection()` will **block forever** in the `BLOCKED` state, waiting for a lock that will never be released.
- **Step 5:** If the thread that should call `resume()` also needs this lock → **DEADLOCK**.

## 3.2 The Safe Alternative — Flag + `wait()` Pattern (Exhaustive Derivation)

> [!NOTE]
> This is the **gold standard** KTU 2024 answer for the "suspend a thread safely" question.

```java
class SafeSuspendibleThread extends Thread {
    private volatile boolean suspended = false;

    public void suspendThread() {
        suspended = true;
    }

    public synchronized void resumeThread() {
        suspended = false;
        notify();   // Wakes up the thread if it is waiting
    }

    public void run() {
        while (true) {
            try {
                synchronized (this) {
                    while (suspended) {
                        System.out.println("Thread paused...");
                        wait();   // Releases the lock on `this`
                    }
                }
                // --- Actual work happens here ---
                System.out.println("Thread is working...");
                Thread.sleep(500);
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                System.out.println("Thread interrupted");
                break;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Logical Deduction

- **Step 1:** A separate control thread invokes `t.suspendThread()`, which sets the `volatile` boolean flag to `true`.
- **Step 2:** The worker thread, on its next loop iteration, enters the `synchronized(this)` block and checks the `while(suspended)` condition.
- **Step 3:** Since `suspended` is `true`, the worker thread calls `this.wait()`.
- **Step 4:** The `wait()` call **atomically releases the lock on `this`**, allowing other threads to acquire it. This is the critical difference from `suspend()`.
- **Step 5:** When `t.resumeThread()` is called, it sets `suspended = false` and calls `notify()`.
- **Step 6:** The worker thread **wakes up**, re-acquires the lock, and the `while` loop condition becomes `false`, allowing it to proceed.

### Why `volatile` is Mandatory

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The `suspended` field is declared `volatile` to ensure **visibility across threads**. Without `volatile`, the worker thread might cache the value and never see the update made by the controller thread — a subtle but critical Java Memory Model requirement frequently asked in KTU exams.

### Analytical Comparison Matrix

| Criterion | `suspend()` (Deprecated) | `wait()` + Flag (Modern) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Releases Monitor Lock | ❌ No (DANGEROUS) | ✅ Yes |
| Risk of Deadlock | ✅ High | ✅ Minimal |
| Thread State After Pause | WAITING | WAITING (via `wait()`) |
| Resume Mechanism | `resume()` method | `notify()` / `notifyAll()` |
| Production Use | ❌ Banned | ✅ Recommended |
| KTU 2024 Exam Weight | ⭐⭐ (Asked for knowledge) | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ (Asked for application) |

