### Question B `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**(a)** With a suitable example, explain how `suspend()` and `resume()` methods work. State two reasons why these methods are deprecated. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Compare and contrast `suspend()` with `wait()`. Write a short program showing how `wait()` can be used to safely pause a thread. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution for (a):

The `suspend()` method, when invoked, immediately **freezes the target thread** at its current instruction. The `resume()` method, when invoked on a previously suspended thread, **causes it to continue execution** from where it stopped.

**Example:**
```java
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.println(i);
            try { Thread.sleep(500); } catch (Exception e) {}
        }
    }
}

public class LegacyDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        MyThread t = new MyThread();
        t.start();
        Thread.sleep(1500);
        t.suspend();   // Freeze
        System.out.println("Suspended");
        Thread.sleep(2000);
        t.resume();    // Continue
        System.out.println("Resumed");
    }
}
```

**Two Reasons for Deprecation (2 marks):**
1. Does not release monitor locks → deadlock risk.
2. Can leave threads in a permanently suspended state if `resume()` is never called.

#### Model Solution for (b):

**Comparison Table (4 marks):**

| Feature | `suspend()` | `wait()` |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Lock released? | No | Yes |
| Class member of | `Thread` | `Object` |
| Resume mechanism | `resume()` | `notify()`/`notifyAll()` |
| Can cause deadlock | Yes | No (if used correctly) |
| Current state | Deprecated | Active, recommended |

**Safe Program Using `wait()` (3 marks):**

```java
class SafePause extends Thread {
    private boolean paused = false;
    public synchronized void pause() { paused = true; }
    public synchronized void unpause() {
        paused = false;
        notify();
    }
    public void run() {
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            try {
                synchronized (this) {
                    while (paused) wait();
                }
                System.out.println("Count: " + i);
                Thread.sleep(500);
            } catch (Exception e) {}
        }
    }
}
```

