# Section 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Event Class Definition (KTU 2024 Scheme):**
> An **Event Class** is a Java class contained within the `java.awt.event` and `java.awt` packages that encapsulates the information generated by an event source (such as a button click, mouse movement, or key press) when a user interacts with a GUI component. Each event class extends `java.util.EventObject` (either directly or via `java.awt.AWTEvent`) and provides accessor methods that allow event listeners to retrieve details like the event type, source, timestamp, coordinates, and modifiers.

In the KTU 2024 syllabus framework for Object Oriented Programming, event classes are positioned as the **data carriers** of the **Delegation Event Model**, which has three participants:

1. **Source** — The object that fires the event.
2. **Event Object** — The class encapsulating state change information.
3. **Listener** — The object that receives and processes the event.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy: The Newspaper Subscription System**
> Imagine you subscribe to a newspaper (the **Listener**). When something newsworthy happens in your city, the reporter (**Source**) files a story. The story itself isn't raw facts — it comes in a **standardized envelope** with fields like *Date*, *Location*, *Category*, and *Headline*. That envelope is the **Event Object (Event Class)**. The reporter fills in those fields based on what happened. You (the listener) read those fields and decide what to do with the information.
>
> In Java:
> - The **envelope** = Event Class instance
> - The **fields** = Methods like `getSource()`, `getID()`, `getX()`, `getY()`
> - The **reporter** = GUI component (e.g., `JButton`)
> - The **subscriber** = Listener implementing the appropriate interface

## 1.3 Why Event Classes Matter in KTU Examinations

- They appear as **2-mark definition questions**, **5-mark hierarchy questions**, and as sub-parts of 14-mark questions on Delegation Event Model.
- The KTU 2024 OBE pattern tags these under **CO4** (Apply event-driven programming concepts to develop GUI applications).
- Students frequently lose marks by confusing **Event Classes** with **Listener Interfaces** — remember, classes are objects fired *by* the source, while listeners are interfaces *implemented by* the handler.

## 1.4 Highlighted Key Constants and Metrics

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Standard Event Metrics to Memorize:**
> - **java.awt.event package location**: `java.awt.event`
> - **Root class**: `java.util.EventObject`
> - **AWT-specific parent**: `java.awt.AWTEvent`
> - **Total semantic event categories in AWT**: **11 primary classes**
> - **Event ID constants**: Static integer fields like `ACTION_PERFORMED = 1001`, `MOUSE_CLICKED = 5001`, `KEY_PRESSED = 401`

