## 5.2 Part B — 14-Mark Questions (Module Internal Choice)

### **Question A (14 Marks)**

#### **Part (a) — 7 Marks**
**[KTU University Exam – July 2024]**
**Draw and explain the AWT event class hierarchy. Discuss any three event classes in detail.**

**Model Answer:**

*(Refer to the hierarchy diagram in Section 4.1)*

The AWT event class hierarchy begins with `java.util.EventObject` as the universal root, extends to `java.awt.AWTEvent`, and branches into eleven concrete event classes that represent different categories of user interactions.

**Three Event Classes in Detail:**

1. **ActionEvent** — Generated when the user activates a component like a `Button` (click) or `MenuItem` (selection). It carries the action command string (typically the button label), modifier keys held during the action, and the timestamp. It fires only `ACTION_PERFORMED` (ID = 1001).

2. **MouseEvent** — Generated when the user interacts with the mouse over any component. It includes spatial data (x, y coordinates), click count (for distinguishing single from double clicks), and button identification. It fires seven distinct event types ranging from `MOUSE_CLICKED` (500) to `MOUSE_DRAGGED` (502).

3. **WindowEvent** — Generated when a `Window`, `Frame`, or `Dialog` undergoes lifecycle changes — opening, closing, activation, deactivation, iconification, and deiconification. It provides access to both the affected window and the opposite window (in activation events).

