#### **Part (b) — 7 Marks**
**[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
**Differentiate between Event Classes and Listener Interfaces in Java AWT. Provide examples of three event classes and their corresponding listener interfaces.**

**Model Answer:**

| Feature | Event Class | Listener Interface |
|---------|-------------|---------------------|
| **Type** | Concrete class (instantiable) | Abstract interface (implementable) |
| **Role** | Carries event data | Defines contract for handling events |
| **Package** | `java.awt.event` | `java.awt.event` |
| **Key Methods** | `getSource()`, `getID()`, accessor methods | Single callback method (e.g., `actionPerformed`) |
| **Created by** | Event source (e.g., Button) | Implemented by application class |
| **Inheritance** | Extends `AWTEvent` | Extends `java.util.EventListener` (marker interface) |

**Examples:**

| Event Class | Listener Interface | Listener Method |
|-------------|--------------------|------------------|
| `ActionEvent` | `ActionListener` | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` |
| `MouseEvent` | `MouseListener` | `mouseClicked(MouseEvent e)` (+ 4 others) |
| `KeyEvent` | `KeyListener` | `keyPressed(KeyEvent e)` (+ 2 others) |

```java
// Demonstrating the difference
ActionEvent ae = new ActionEvent(btn, 1001, "OK");  // Event class instantiated

class MyHandler implements ActionListener {          // Listener interface implemented
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {    // Handler method receives event class
        System.out.println(e.getActionCommand());
    }
}
```

*(7 marks: 2 for comparison table + 3 for examples + 2 for code demonstration)*

