## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes That Cost Marks in KTU Board Exams:**
>
> 1. **Confusing Event Classes with Listener Interfaces** — Event classes are *objects fired by sources*; listener interfaces are *contracts implemented by handlers*. Examiners specifically check this distinction.
>
> 2. **Forgetting to override ALL methods** — If a class implements `MouseListener`, it must provide bodies for **all 5 methods** (`mouseClicked`, `mouseEntered`, `mouseExited`, `mousePressed`, `mouseReleased`), even if 4 of them are empty. Missing even one triggers compilation failure.
>
> 3. **Not calling `setFocusable(true)`** — In KeyEvent programs, the frame will not receive keys unless it has focus. This is the **#1 reason** "KeyListener is not working" in student submissions.
>
> 4. **Casting `getSource()` incorrectly** — `getSource()` returns `Object`. You must cast to the actual source type (`Button b = (Button) e.getSource();`). Forgetting the cast loses marks.
>
> 5. **Mixing up `getKeyChar()` vs `getKeyCode()`** — `getKeyChar()` returns the **character produced** (e.g., 'A' or 'a' depending on Shift). `getKeyCode()` returns the **virtual key code** (e.g., `VK_A = 65`). Use `getKeyChar()` for typed input, `getKeyCode()` for arrow keys / function keys.
>
> 6. **Wrong package import** — Event classes are in `java.awt.event`, **not** `java.awt`. Forgetting this import is a silent killer.

